The paper deals with the axiomatization of interactive small-step algorithms, which involves logical reasoning and formal methods, suggesting that it could belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The paper also discusses the behavior of algorithms, which could fall under Programming Languages (cs.PL) and Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. The use of abstract state machines and the extension of the thesis to cover non-ordinary algorithms suggest that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the order in which replies are received, which could relate to Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL).
